The entirety of New York City’s public school system will close on Thursday as the city battles a second wave of Coronavirus. Chancellor Richard A. Carranza made the announcement to school principals in an email on Wednesday. Moving to all-remote instruction will disrupt the education of many of the roughly 300,000 children who have been attending in-person classes in the city.
Anna Watts for The New York Times The shutdown was decided upon after the city hit a three per cent positivity rate over a seven-day rolling average. Schools within the system will now move classes online — no less 300,000 children are expected to be affected. So far, New York City has recorded 290,000 cases of the virus while 24,146 have died from it.